<p class="lead">One of the most common — and most expensive — misconceptions we hear from new Michigan business owners is "I formed an LLC, so I don't really need insurance." An LLC is a valuable legal structure, but it does a very different job than an insurance policy, and confusing the two leaves a lot of owners exposed. Here's what an LLC actually protects, what it doesn't, and the coverage that fills the gap.</p>

<h2>What an LLC does — and doesn't — do</h2>
<p>A limited liability company creates a legal separation between your business and your personal assets. If the business is sued or owes a debt, that separation can keep creditors from reaching your house, your car, and your personal savings. That's real protection, and it's worth having.</p>
<p>But notice what it does <em>not</em> do:</p>
<ul>
  <li><strong>It doesn't pay claims.</strong> If a customer is injured or you damage someone's property, the LLC shields your personal assets — but the <em>business</em> still has to pay the judgment or settlement, which can wipe out the company you built.</li>
  <li><strong>It doesn't cover your own property.</strong> An LLC offers zero protection for your tools, inventory, equipment, or building if there's a fire, theft, or storm.</li>
  <li><strong>It doesn't protect you from your own negligence.</strong> Courts can hold an owner personally responsible for their own professional mistakes or actions, LLC or not.</li>
  <li><strong>The shield can be "pierced."</strong> If you commingle personal and business finances or don't maintain the LLC properly, a court can set the protection aside and reach your personal assets anyway.</li>
</ul>
<p>In short: an LLC limits <em>who</em> can be reached in a lawsuit. Insurance pays the actual bill. You want both.</p>

<h2>Sole proprietors: even more exposed</h2>
<p>If you haven't formed an LLC or corporation at all, you're a sole proprietor by default — and there is <strong>no legal separation</strong> between you and your business. A lawsuit or business debt can come straight for your personal assets. For a sole proprietor, business insurance isn't just protecting the company; it's protecting your home and savings directly. Many Michigan sole proprietors are one accident away from a personal financial crisis without realizing it.</p>

<h2>Coverages that actually matter for small businesses</h2>
<ul>
  <li><strong>General Liability (GL).</strong> The foundation. Covers third-party bodily injury and property damage — the customer who slips, the equipment you accidentally damage on a job. Most clients, landlords, and contracts require it.</li>
  <li><strong>Business Owner's Policy (BOP).</strong> Bundles general liability with property coverage for your equipment, inventory, and space — usually the most cost-effective package for a small business.</li>
  <li><strong>Professional Liability (E&O).</strong> If you give advice or provide a professional service, this covers claims that your work caused a financial loss. GL won't.</li>
  <li><strong>Commercial Auto.</strong> If you or employees drive for the business, your personal auto policy likely excludes business use. (We cover this in detail in our commercial auto article.)</li>
  <li><strong><a href="../../business/workers-compensation/">Workers' Compensation</a>.</strong> In Michigan, workers' comp is generally required once you have employees — the thresholds are specific, and the penalties for going without are steep.</li>
</ul>

<h2>Why clients and landlords will ask anyway</h2>
<p>Even if you're comfortable with the risk, the market often isn't. Commercial landlords, general contractors, and larger customers routinely require a <strong>certificate of insurance</strong> — proof of general liability, sometimes with specific limits — before they'll sign a lease, let you on a job site, or hire you. Without coverage, you simply can't take the work. An LLC certificate won't satisfy that requirement; a liability policy will.</p>

<h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>
<h3>If I have an LLC, do I still need business insurance?</h3>
<p>Yes. An LLC limits which assets a lawsuit can reach, but it doesn't pay claims or cover your own equipment and property — insurance does. The two work together.</p>
<h3>Does a sole proprietor need business insurance?</h3>
<p>Even more so. A sole proprietor has no legal separation between business and personal assets, so a claim or judgment can reach your home and savings directly.</p>
<h3>What coverage does a small Michigan business usually start with?</h3>
<p>General liability — often bundled into a <a href="../../business/">Business Owner's Policy</a> with property coverage — plus <a href="../../business/workers-compensation/">workers' compensation</a> once you have employees, and professional liability if you give advice or provide a service.</p>

<h2>The bottom line</h2>
<p>An LLC and business insurance solve two different problems: the LLC limits which assets are exposed, and insurance pays the claim so it never gets that far. Relying on the LLC alone leaves your business — and, if you're a sole proprietor, your personal finances — open to the very losses you formed the company to avoid. The good news is that coverage for a small Michigan business is usually more affordable than owners expect. Tell us what you do and we'll build the right combination of liability, property, and required coverages — and get you the certificate your clients are asking for.</p>
